# 28-OSPF Part 1 – Basics and Single-Area Fundamentals

## Overview

This lesson introduces OSPF, the main dynamic routing protocol you need for the CCNA.

OSPF stands for Open Shortest Path First.

It is the only dynamic routing protocol explicitly named in the CCNA exam topics, so it matters much more than RIP and EIGRP.

This first lesson is a high-level introduction. It focuses on:

- basic OSPF operation
- OSPF areas
- basic OSPF configuration
- core terminology you must recognize before going deeper

---

## OSPF Position in Routing Protocols

OSPF is a:

- dynamic routing protocol
- IGP (Interior Gateway Protocol)
- link-state protocol

That means it works differently from RIP and EIGRP.

### Reminder: Distance Vector vs Link State

#### Distance Vector
Examples:

- RIP
- EIGRP

Behavior:

- routers learn routes from neighbors
- routers do not have a full map of the network
- routers rely on what neighbors tell them

This is often described as "routing by rumor".

---

#### Link State
Examples:

- OSPF
- IS-IS

Behavior:

- routers build a map of the network
- routers exchange topology information
- each router calculates the best path itself

This gives better decisions and faster reaction to changes, but requires more CPU and memory.

---

## OSPF Versions

There are 3 versions of OSPF:

- OSPFv1: old, not used
- OSPFv2: mainly for IPv4
- OSPFv3: mainly for IPv6, can also support IPv4

For CCNA, the important one is:

- OSPFv2

That is the version referenced in the exam topics.

---

## OSPF Core Algorithm

OSPF uses the SPF algorithm:

- Shortest Path First

Another name:

- Dijkstra’s algorithm

This is a very important name to remember.

OSPF uses this algorithm to calculate the best path to each destination after building its topology database.

---

## How OSPF Works at a High Level

OSPF works in 3 major stages:

1. Become neighbors with directly connected OSPF routers
2. Exchange LSAs and build the LSDB
3. Run the SPF algorithm to calculate best routes

---

## Important OSPF Terms

### LSA
LSA = Link State Advertisement

An LSA is a piece of OSPF information that describes part of the network.

Examples of information carried in LSAs:

- router ID
- connected networks
- interface costs
- topology information

Routers generate LSAs and flood them through the OSPF area.

---

### LSDB
LSDB = Link State Database

This is the database where routers store LSAs.

Key idea:

- all routers in the same OSPF area should have the same LSDB

That shared database is what lets every router calculate the network the same way.

---

### Flooding
Flooding means:

- sending LSAs to all OSPF neighbors so the information spreads through the area

This is how all routers end up with the same LSDB.

---

## Example OSPF Logic

If R4 activates OSPF on a new interface and adds a new subnet:

- R4 creates an LSA describing that link
- R4 sends it to its neighbors
- neighbors flood it onward
- all routers in the area learn about it
- all routers update their LSDB
- all routers run SPF again
- all routers recalculate best routes

This is one of the main strengths of OSPF.

---

## OSPF Metric

OSPF uses a metric called:

- cost

Lower cost = better route

You will study cost in more detail later, but for now:

- OSPF chooses the path with the lowest total cost

---

## OSPF Areas

Areas are one of the most important OSPF concepts.

OSPF can divide a larger network into smaller logical sections called areas.

### Why areas exist

In small networks, one area is fine.

In large networks, one huge OSPF area creates problems:

- larger LSDB
- more CPU use during SPF calculations
- more memory use
- more flooding when topology changes
- slower overall behavior

So OSPF uses areas to scale.

---

## Single-Area OSPF

For the CCNA, you only need to configure:

- single-area OSPF

Usually that means:

- area 0

In small networks, using one area is normal and efficient.

---

## OSPF Backbone Area

Area 0 is special.

It is called:

- the backbone area

Important rule:

- all other OSPF areas must connect to area 0

If an area does not connect to area 0 properly, OSPF design is broken.

---

## OSPF Area Rules

### Rule 1: Areas should be contiguous

A single OSPF area must stay connected.

Bad design:

- one area split into disconnected pieces

Good design:

- if a section is separated, make it another area

---

### Rule 2: Non-backbone areas must connect to area 0 through an ABR

Every area outside area 0 must have at least one Area Border Router connected to area 0.

---

### Rule 3: Interfaces in the same subnet must be in the same OSPF area

If two routers are on the same subnet but configured in different OSPF areas:

- they will not become OSPF neighbors

This is a very common source of configuration problems.

---

## OSPF Router Types

### Internal Router

A router with all interfaces in the same OSPF area.

Example:

- all interfaces in area 1

Then that router is an internal router for area 1.

---

### ABR
ABR = Area Border Router

A router with interfaces in multiple OSPF areas.

Example:

- one interface in area 0
- one interface in area 1

That router is an ABR.

Important note:

- an ABR keeps a separate LSDB for each area it connects to
- best practice is usually no more than 2 areas per ABR

---

### Backbone Router

A router with at least one interface in area 0.

That includes:

- internal routers in area 0
- ABRs connected to area 0

---

### ASBR
ASBR = Autonomous System Boundary Router

A router that connects the OSPF domain to an external network.

Typical example:

- a router connected to the Internet
- advertising a default route into OSPF

---

## Route Types in OSPF

### Intra-Area Route

A route to a destination inside the same OSPF area.

Example:

- router in area 1 learning a network also in area 1

---

### Interarea Route

A route to a destination in a different OSPF area.

Example:

- router in area 1 learning a network in area 2

---

## Basic OSPF Configuration

### Enter OSPF Process

```bash
router ospf 1
```

The number is the process ID.

Important points:

- process ID is locally significant
- neighbors do not need to use the same process ID
- process ID is not the area number

This is different from EIGRP, where the AS number must match.

---

## OSPF `network` Command

Example:

```bash
network 10.0.12.0 0.0.0.15 area 0
```

OSPF uses wildcard masks, just like EIGRP.

Purpose of the command:

- match interfaces whose IP addresses fall in that range
- activate OSPF on those interfaces
- place those interfaces in the specified area

Important:

- the area is mandatory in OSPF
- unlike EIGRP/RIP, the command is incomplete without the area

---

## What the OSPF Network Command Really Does

The command does **not** directly say:

- advertise this exact prefix

Instead it says:

- look for interfaces matching this range
- enable OSPF there
- assign the interface to that area
- begin neighbor discovery on that interface

Then the router will advertise the connected subnet through LSAs.

---

## OSPF Passive Interface

Same idea as in RIP and EIGRP:

```bash
passive-interface g2/0
```

Purpose:

- stop sending OSPF hello packets out that interface
- still advertise the connected subnet into OSPF

Use it on interfaces where:

- OSPF should advertise the subnet
- but no OSPF neighbors exist on that segment

Good example:

- LAN interface connected only to hosts

---

## OSPF Default Route Advertisement

If the router already has a default route and you want to inject it into OSPF:

```bash
default-information originate
```

This causes the router to advertise the default route to OSPF neighbors.

That usually makes the router an:

- ASBR

Because it is now connecting the OSPF domain to an external path.

---

## OSPF Router ID

OSPF uses a router ID, just like EIGRP.

Router ID selection order:

1. manually configured router ID
2. highest IP on a loopback interface
3. highest IP on a physical interface

Example manual configuration:

```bash
router-id 1.1.1.1
```

Important:

- in OSPF, the command is `router-id`
- in EIGRP, it was `eigrp router-id`

---

## Applying a New Router ID

If you manually configure a new OSPF router ID, it does not always take effect immediately.

You may need to reset the OSPF process:

```bash
clear ip ospf process
```

Warning:

- this resets OSPF on the router
- neighbors drop temporarily
- routes are lost briefly
- safe in lab, risky in production

---

## OSPF Verification Commands

### `show ip protocols`

Useful information shown:

- protocol running
- process ID
- router ID
- passive interfaces
- OSPF neighbors
- configured networks
- maximum paths
- administrative distance

---

### `show ip route`

Used to see OSPF routes in the routing table.

OSPF routes appear with code:

- `O`

Default route learned through OSPF also appears there if successfully advertised.

---

## OSPF Maximum Paths

Like RIP and EIGRP, OSPF supports ECMP.

Default:

- up to 4 equal-cost paths

Can be changed with:

```bash
maximum-paths 8
```

This only affects equal-cost routes, not unequal-cost balancing.

---

## OSPF Administrative Distance

Default OSPF AD:

- 110

Can be changed with:

```bash
distance 85
```

This changes route preference relative to other protocols on that router.

---

## OSPF and ASBR

If a router injects a default route into OSPF, it becomes an ASBR.

Example situation:

- router connected to Internet
- has a static default route
- uses `default-information originate`

Result:

- OSPF neighbors learn the default route
- router is now acting as an Autonomous System Boundary Router

---

## Things to Remember About OSPF Configuration

### Similar to RIP/EIGRP
- `passive-interface`
- `maximum-paths`
- `distance`
- dynamic routing process mode
- router ID concept

### Different from RIP/EIGRP
- process ID is local only
- `network` command requires area
- OSPF uses LSAs and LSDB
- areas are a core design concept

---

## Key Exam-Level Facts

- OSPF is a link-state IGP
- OSPF uses Dijkstra’s SPF algorithm
- OSPFv2 is the important IPv4 version for CCNA
- area 0 is the backbone area
- all non-backbone areas must connect to area 0
- interfaces in the same subnet must be in the same OSPF area
- process IDs do not need to match between neighbors
- OSPF network commands require an area
- `default-information originate` advertises a default route
- router ID priority: manual > loopback > physical
- OSPF route code = `O`
- OSPF AD = 110

---

## Mental Model

Think of OSPF like this:

- routers become neighbors
- routers exchange topology information, not just routes
- all routers in an area build the same map
- each router calculates the best paths itself

That is the key difference from distance-vector protocols.

